00:00:01.14 --> 00:00:02.61
That was earlier today.

00:00:02.61 --> 00:00:05.34
Early voting in Texas is underway

00:00:05.34 --> 00:00:08.46
in the Democratic primary for the state's 28th Congressional

00:00:08.46 --> 00:00:09.48
District.

00:00:09.48 --> 00:00:12.00
The seat currently belongs to Henry Cuellar.

00:00:12.00 --> 00:00:15.00
He's been in Congress since 2005, but back in January,

00:00:15.00 --> 00:00:18.42
his home was raided as part of an FBI investigation

00:00:18.42 --> 00:00:21.99
into Azerbaijan and several US businessmen.

00:00:21.99 --> 00:00:25.23
Cuellar's toughest competitor is progressive candidate Jessica

00:00:25.23 --> 00:00:25.98
Cisneros.

00:00:25.98 --> 00:00:28.56
The immigration attorney previously ran against Cuellar

00:00:28.56 --> 00:00:29.58
in 2020.

00:00:29.58 --> 00:00:34.35
She lost that primary battle by a little less than 2,700 votes.

00:00:34.35 --> 00:00:37.44
This year's primary is on March 1.

00:00:37.44 --> 00:00:40.98
Aaron Navarro is from the CBS News political unit

00:00:40.98 --> 00:00:42.97
and is here with us.

00:00:42.97 --> 00:00:44.88
He has been following that race.

00:00:44.88 --> 00:00:47.43
Aaron, I understand that Cisneros

00:00:47.43 --> 00:00:51.06
has been endorsed by the progressive wing of the party

00:00:51.06 --> 00:00:52.83
like AOC, like Bernie Sanders.

00:00:52.83 --> 00:00:55.83
But you have talked directly to voters

00:00:55.83 --> 00:00:59.91
about how they felt about this FBI raid at Cuellar's home.

00:00:59.91 --> 00:01:03.52
Let's take a listen first and get back to you.

00:01:03.52 --> 00:01:07.20
The fact that politicians have to raise so much money--

00:01:07.20 --> 00:01:09.63
and this is all of them, right?

00:01:09.63 --> 00:01:14.46
They are forced to raise all of this money continuously

00:01:14.46 --> 00:01:18.24
in order to support their offices, the travel, the work

00:01:18.24 --> 00:01:19.72
that they do.

00:01:19.72 --> 00:01:25.29
And so it doesn't surprise me that sometimes people

00:01:25.29 --> 00:01:26.54
can take advantage of that.

00:01:26.54 --> 00:01:28.21
A lot of that stuff doesn't surprise me.

00:01:28.21 --> 00:01:29.79
I just follow the candidates who don't

00:01:29.79 --> 00:01:33.96
accept political contributions from companies and high donors.

00:01:33.96 --> 00:01:37.32
I just feel they're more prone to corruption.

00:01:37.32 --> 00:01:40.08
Well, you know the FBI raid was not a good look.

00:01:40.08 --> 00:01:44.37
But, Aaron, what's your sense on how the FBI investigation is

00:01:44.37 --> 00:01:46.20
impacting this race, if at all?

00:01:46.20 --> 00:01:49.03


00:01:49.03 --> 00:01:49.53
Hi, Lilia.

00:01:49.53 --> 00:01:50.44
Thanks for having me.

00:01:50.44 --> 00:01:52.41
So it depends who you ask, really,

00:01:52.41 --> 00:01:54.36
but it seems like from our conversations

00:01:54.36 --> 00:01:57.15
with voters is that it hasn't changed anyone's mind

00:01:57.15 --> 00:01:58.44
that was already made up.

00:01:58.44 --> 00:02:01.02
As you mentioned, Cuellar has represented this district

00:02:01.02 --> 00:02:04.53
since 2005, so a good amount of constituents already know him

00:02:04.53 --> 00:02:06.24
and how they feel about him, and it

00:02:06.24 --> 00:02:08.40
seems like he's retaining that support.

00:02:08.40 --> 00:02:10.90
His campaign claims the impact has been,

00:02:10.90 --> 00:02:12.88
quote, unquote, "minimal" on the race,

00:02:12.88 --> 00:02:14.46
and we had a couple voters that seemed

00:02:14.46 --> 00:02:16.92
to weigh the raid at a lower level compared

00:02:16.92 --> 00:02:19.74
to his work in the district, particularly on the border

00:02:19.74 --> 00:02:21.45
and money he's brought to the district

00:02:21.45 --> 00:02:23.91
through his role on the House Appropriations Committee.

00:02:23.91 --> 00:02:25.62
And when you talk to progressives,

00:02:25.62 --> 00:02:27.66
they say that the raid confirms what they already

00:02:27.66 --> 00:02:29.23
thought about Cuellar, that he is,

00:02:29.23 --> 00:02:31.23
quote, unquote, bought by corporate PACs

00:02:31.23 --> 00:02:32.37
and outside interests.

00:02:32.37 --> 00:02:34.75
But they were already looking to vote for Cisneros

00:02:34.75 --> 00:02:36.21
through the issues like health care

00:02:36.21 --> 00:02:39.09
and raising the minimum wage, so the direct impact

00:02:39.09 --> 00:02:43.42
of the raid actually changing minds remains to be seen.

00:02:43.42 --> 00:02:47.58
I mean, the gap between them was so small.

00:02:47.58 --> 00:02:50.22
I mean that margin in votes last time around.

00:02:50.22 --> 00:02:51.78
What's different this time around?

00:02:51.78 --> 00:02:54.09
Of course if I were a politician,

00:02:54.09 --> 00:02:57.00
I'd be running on that FBI raid.

00:02:57.00 --> 00:03:00.40
And I'm sure if Cuellar were to win the nomination,

00:03:00.40 --> 00:03:04.53
then he would be facing very harsh ads, perhaps,

00:03:04.53 --> 00:03:05.88
from the Republican candidate.

00:03:05.88 --> 00:03:07.59
But what is Cisneros doing?

00:03:07.59 --> 00:03:08.31
What's at stake?

00:03:08.31 --> 00:03:12.24
Tell me a little bit more about her run this time around.

00:03:12.24 --> 00:03:13.11
Sure.

00:03:13.11 --> 00:03:17.25
And Cisneros immediately after the FBI raid,

00:03:17.25 --> 00:03:20.13
her and the Justice Democrats group that is backing her

00:03:20.13 --> 00:03:22.44
did run ads about this race.

00:03:22.44 --> 00:03:25.38
But when it comes to what's different

00:03:25.38 --> 00:03:27.84
this go around is the fact that you

00:03:27.84 --> 00:03:30.12
have a bit of a different kind of district.

00:03:30.12 --> 00:03:32.82
The new map puts a bit more of San Antonio

00:03:32.82 --> 00:03:34.59
and some rural counties into the district,

00:03:34.59 --> 00:03:37.35
and that is where Cisneros says the FBI

00:03:37.35 --> 00:03:40.05
raid could make an impact because there are new voters.

00:03:40.05 --> 00:03:41.97
We talked to Jessica Cisneros on the trail,

00:03:41.97 --> 00:03:44.73
and here's what she had to say about the new map.

00:03:44.73 --> 00:03:47.16
I think we're focusing a lot on the areas that

00:03:47.16 --> 00:03:50.01
are new to our district, including some of the two

00:03:50.01 --> 00:03:53.94
counties around here, which are Duval and Jim Hogg,

00:03:53.94 --> 00:03:55.95
and then also introducing our campaign

00:03:55.95 --> 00:03:59.22
to those in the northern part of San Antonio and Guadalupe

00:03:59.22 --> 00:04:01.26
County.

00:04:01.26 --> 00:04:03.48
We were able to put our race in front

00:04:03.48 --> 00:04:05.91
of so many Democratic voters last time around,

00:04:05.91 --> 00:04:08.04
but the district is now new, right?

00:04:08.04 --> 00:04:11.13
There's newer components to it, so it's allowed us--

00:04:11.13 --> 00:04:14.44
the fact that people in the old district know who we are,

00:04:14.44 --> 00:04:18.21
it's allowed us to dedicate space and resources

00:04:18.21 --> 00:04:20.13
to introduce our campaign to those new voters.

00:04:20.13 --> 00:04:22.74
So for us, it's making sure that they know who we are

00:04:22.74 --> 00:04:24.00
and turning them out.

00:04:24.00 --> 00:04:26.76
And I think it's not a good first impression

00:04:26.76 --> 00:04:29.10
for a lot of those voters that the incumbent has

00:04:29.10 --> 00:04:33.27
been subjected to an FBI raid so close to the election.

00:04:33.27 --> 00:04:36.12
There seem to be such stark differences between these two

00:04:36.12 --> 00:04:36.87
candidates.

00:04:36.87 --> 00:04:39.18
What does this race mean for the progressive movement

00:04:39.18 --> 00:04:43.23
at large within the Democratic Party?

00:04:43.23 --> 00:04:46.08
So off bat, this is the first true test

00:04:46.08 --> 00:04:48.90
of progressive energy in a cycle that looks a bit

00:04:48.90 --> 00:04:50.37
unfavorable for Democrats.

00:04:50.37 --> 00:04:53.99
In 2018 when you had candidates like Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez,

00:04:53.99 --> 00:04:56.16
they were going into an environment that looked good

00:04:56.16 --> 00:04:58.56
for House Democrats, and in 2020, they

00:04:58.56 --> 00:05:00.90
seemed that they were poised to keep the majority,

00:05:00.90 --> 00:05:01.62
and they did.

00:05:01.62 --> 00:05:03.87
And you also have a handful of progressive challengers

00:05:03.87 --> 00:05:07.28
this election cycle where a Cisneros win or loss could give

00:05:07.28 --> 00:05:09.81
a lot of tea leaves for the rest of the challengers

00:05:09.81 --> 00:05:11.31
and how those races could go.

00:05:11.31 --> 00:05:13.26
And secondly, progressives have gone

00:05:13.26 --> 00:05:16.41
after moderate members over the stall in President Biden's

00:05:16.41 --> 00:05:17.43
agenda.

00:05:17.43 --> 00:05:20.25
Congresswoman Ocasio-Cortez rallied for Cisneros

00:05:20.25 --> 00:05:22.95
this past weekend, and part of her rally remarks

00:05:22.95 --> 00:05:25.56
were like, look, it's not just Joe Manchin or Kyrsten

00:05:25.56 --> 00:05:27.54
Sinema that's blocking the Biden agenda.

00:05:27.54 --> 00:05:30.42
It's moderate House Democrats like Henry Cuellar that

00:05:30.42 --> 00:05:32.16
pushed for the passing of infrastructure

00:05:32.16 --> 00:05:34.08
without the Build Back Better plan.

00:05:34.08 --> 00:05:36.75
If Cisneros wins this, you can expect progressives

00:05:36.75 --> 00:05:40.38
to incorporate bringing up the [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:40.38 --> 00:05:42.78
on the trail in their own challenges.

00:05:42.78 --> 00:05:45.48
Not to mention Cuellar's position on abortion rights

00:05:45.48 --> 00:05:46.59
too.

00:05:46.59 --> 00:05:49.20
Republicans are looking to play in this district in November,

00:05:49.20 --> 00:05:52.89
of course, even though it has been historically Democratic.

00:05:52.89 --> 00:05:57.07
What do you think that is all about?

00:05:57.07 --> 00:05:59.37
So it mainly stems from the gains

00:05:59.37 --> 00:06:02.91
they were able to make in 2020 in south Texas

00:06:02.91 --> 00:06:04.47
and with the Hispanic community.

00:06:04.47 --> 00:06:06.37
They were able to flip Zapata County, which

00:06:06.37 --> 00:06:07.20
is in this district.

00:06:07.20 --> 00:06:09.42
It's a more rural area in the district.

00:06:09.42 --> 00:06:11.82
And Zapata County went from voting

00:06:11.82 --> 00:06:16.02
for Hillary Clinton in 2016 by 33 points to President Trump

00:06:16.02 --> 00:06:17.13
by 6 points.

00:06:17.13 --> 00:06:20.25
And while Cuellar still won that county in his general election

00:06:20.25 --> 00:06:23.61
race in November of 2020, that's a pretty big shift.

00:06:23.61 --> 00:06:25.32
Republicans are looking to build on this.

00:06:25.32 --> 00:06:27.06
They have established community centers

00:06:27.06 --> 00:06:29.01
in Laredo and San Antonio.

00:06:29.01 --> 00:06:30.84
A lot of the Republican officials and voters

00:06:30.84 --> 00:06:32.31
we talked to say they've just been

00:06:32.31 --> 00:06:36.00
able to be more vocal about their political stances

00:06:36.00 --> 00:06:37.74
as the margins get better for them.

00:06:37.74 --> 00:06:39.96
They say the party stances on immigration

00:06:39.96 --> 00:06:42.03
and conservative social values such as being

00:06:42.03 --> 00:06:44.72
antiabortion resonate with certain communities

00:06:44.72 --> 00:06:45.39
in the district.

00:06:45.39 --> 00:06:49.34
And lastly, right next to this district you have Texas's 15.

00:06:49.34 --> 00:06:52.19
That's an open seat left by House Democrat Vicente

00:06:52.19 --> 00:06:55.28
Gonzalez, who decided to run in a politically safer seat,

00:06:55.28 --> 00:06:58.37
and that is one of the prime pickup opportunities

00:06:58.37 --> 00:06:59.51
for House Republicans.

00:06:59.51 --> 00:07:01.73
So you have another district that's

00:07:01.73 --> 00:07:04.04
pretty similar at play, similar trends

00:07:04.04 --> 00:07:06.23
there in the Texas 28th district.

00:07:06.23 --> 00:07:09.47
The Republicans are definitely looking to make a play.

00:07:09.47 --> 00:07:12.02
Aaron Navarro, thank you so much for breaking this

00:07:12.02 --> 00:07:14.22
all down for us.

00:07:14.22 --> 00:07:16.00
